Summary: Request for current state of crypto in US
Keywords: DES, crypto

In a recent discussion on CIX (UK BBS) jules@cix.compulink.co.uk made this
statement which I repost with his permission, I feel it is overly paranoid,
what does the panel think?
> 
> Well, without going into chapter and verse (which is extensively 
> documented elsewhere..)
> 
> The DES, which you've no doubt heard of.  The maths and research is 
> still secret, and people who know anything about it can go to prison for 
> talking about it.  The secret to DES is in the encryption tables, (which 
> were secret until recently) and it seems that a trapdoor has been 
> deliberately inserted into these tables to allow people with big enough 
> computers (read, the CIA and the FBI) to crack any message encrypted 
> with DES.  A small modification to the tables closes this trapdoor, as 
> does longer keys.  Both these measures have been explicitly banned by 
> law now.  In principle, all internal communications, and comms entering 
> the US, must be encrypted with DES.
> 
> Leaving aside the fact that any encryption scheme based on secrecy of 
> the method is inherently falwed, the objection to this is that right now 
> the KGB also has big computers, as do various agencies in the middle 
> east, and in five years time that kind of welly will be sitting on every 
> desktop in the country.  Furthermore, there are even three electonics 
> companies currently marketing DES cracker chips.  The DES is no 
> encryption at all.  Now many agencies, and even the phone companies, are 
> operating in violation of the law by using other encryption techniques.
> 
> This is coming to a head right now, with several phone companies being 
> prosecuted.  There is another law which says that every phone exchange 
> must provide assitance to the intelligence and law-enforcement agencies 
> BBwith the tapping of phone lines, under certain circumstances.  Because 
> the phones are using encryption other than DES, they must provide 
> decrypt facilities, and they can't, because they've selected 
> 'uncrackable' methods.  They've bought the equipment, and are using it, 
> and are being dragged through the courts right now.  As a result of the 
> publicity, there is a concerted campaign by civil liberties 
> organisations to get the tapping law removed.
> 
> While all this is going on, several other people have been working on 
> encryption in the US.  Many of those people have had to leave the US and 
> publish elsewhere, and many are in prison on a variety of charges.
> 
